SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$BR $SPACE $BR 
$BBOLD  SOLUTION $EBOLD
$BR 
The continuous percent growth rate is the value of $BITALIC k $EITALIC in the equation \( Q=ae^{kt} \), which is $k.  To convert to the form \( Q=ab^t \), we first say that the right sides of the two equations equal each other (since each equals $BITALIC Q${EITALIC}), and then we solve for $BITALIC a $EITALIC and $BITALIC b $EITALIC.  Thus, we have \( ab^{t}= $a e^{$k t} \).  At $BITALIC t $EITALIC = 0, we can solve for $BITALIC a${EITALIC}: $BR $SPACE $BR

\( \ \ \ \ \ \ ab^{0} = $a e^{$k \cdot 0} \) $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ a \cdot 1 = $a \cdot 1 \) $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ a = $a \). $BR $SPACE $BR

Thus, we have \( $a b^{t} = $a e^{$k t} \), and we solve for \( b \): $BR $SPACE $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ $a b^t = $a e^{$k t} \) $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ b^{t} = e^{$k t} \) $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ b^t = \left( e^{$k} \right)^t \) $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ b = e^{$k} \approx $b \). $BR $SPACE $BR

Therefore, the equation is \( Q = $a \cdot ($b)^{t} \).
$BR
END_SOLUTION
 

